== Ottoman Structures in Peja ==
''See also: [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ottoman_architecture Ottoman Architecture] and [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bazaar Bazaar]''
[[File:<U+00C7>arshia e gjat<U+00EB> e Pej<U+00EB>s.jpg|thumb|300x300px|Bazaar of Peja serves as the main market for Gold shops]]

=== Bazaar of Peja ===
The [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bazaar Bazaar] of Peja is located in the center
of the city located near the river between parallel residence zones and is a remnant of the Ottoman rule there. The earliest mention of the Bazaar of Peja according to some sources is around the XIV century. The market historically housed blacksmiths and carpenters but also facilitated the agricultural market.<ref>Instituti per Mbrojtjen e Monumenteve te Kultures:Monumentet kulturo-historike. Peje: Litografia, 2006. (Albanian)</ref>

The Bazaar of Peja or Pazar (Albanian) has mainly an Ottoman architecture on the buildings, which mainly serve as stores today.

The Bazaar of Peja was completely destroyed at least twice, once during the Italian occupation in 1943, and once during the 1999 war in Kosovo. Today the Bazaar of Peja, or locally known as <U+00C7>arshia e Gjat<U+00EB>, is fully rebuilt (after the 1999 war) and still keeps the ottoman architecture, and is the main market in the city of Peja, and is one of the many monuments which are under protection by the law.<ref>CHwB-Trashegimia Kulturore pa Kufij:Konservimi i Integruar. Prishtine:2011.(Albanian)</ref>

<gallery>File:Qarshia_e_Pejes_1.jpg|Bazaar of Peja shown with many shops closed on a Sunday
File:Qarshia_e_Pejes.jpg| Bazaar of Peja closed on a Sunday
File:Qarshia_e_gjate.JPG|Bazaar of Peja</gallery>
[[File:Bajrakli Xhami.JPG|thumb|251x251px|Bajrakli Mosque]]

=== Bajrakli Mosque (<U+00C7>arshi Xhamia) ===
Is the main mosque situated in the center of the Bazaar of Peja. It was built in 1471 by Sultan Fatih Mehmet Hani and is an ottoman style mosque with the oldest and highest dome in the city. The Bajrakli Xhamia is a single domed mosque which is one of the main three architectural types of mosques in ottoman architecture. This style dates from the early ottoman period.<ref>[http://books.google.com/books?id=EhIjXjCVQyYC&printsec=frontcover&dq=the+oxford+history+of+islam&hl=en&sa=X&ei=FQUSU8HxNqf8ywPe7ILACA&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=the%20oxford%20history%20of%20islam&f=false], Sultanates and Gunpowder Empires, Ira M. Lapidus, The Oxford History of Islam, Ed. John L. Esposito, (Oxford University Press, 1999), 371.</ref>

The Bajrakli Xhamia was burned down once during 1943 by Italian forces when the Bazaar of Peja was completely burned down, however it was not destroyed during the 1999 War in Kosovo.<ref>Instituti per Mbrojtjen e Monumenteve te Kultures:Monumentet kulturo-historike. Peje: Litografia, 2006. (Albanian)</ref>

=== The Old Bath (Hammam) ===
''See also: [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turkish_bath Hammam]''
[[File:Old Bath Peja.jpg|thumb|274x274px|The Old Bath seen from outside|left]]
The Hammam is built similarly to Turkish Baths with ottoman architecture. It was built under ottoman rule and belonged to the Dukagjini Sandzak (1462<U+2013>1485).<ref>CHwB-Trashegimia Kulturore pa Kufij:Konservimi i Integruar. Prishtine:2011.(Albanian)</ref> The building has an asymmetric <U+201C>double<U+201D> bath. According to some sources the bath was 

reconstructed in 1861 because of unkown reasons. <ref>[http://books.google.com/books?id=uSaH1bKAb8QC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=150&f=false]Gail Warrander and Venera Knaus:Kosovo.USA:Bradt Travel Guide, 2008 p.159</ref>

The bath has <U+201C> an entrance area wordrobe, separation and insulation chambers, perspmation-massage-bathing area, and water storange and furnace chamber. The Hammam has a quadraregular foundation and the material that was used to build it was stone and bricks produced with an <U+2018>opus mixum<U+2019><U+2019>technique<U+2019><U+2019>. The bath is a Turkish Bath type of bath.<ref>CHwB-Trashegimia Kulturore pa Kufij:Konservimi i Integruar. Prishtine:2011.(Albanian)</ref>

The bath was damaged during war and was reconstructed after. Today, the hammam serves as an exhibition hall for different art shows and more.<ref>[http://books.google.com/books?id=uSaH1bKAb8QC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=150&f=false]Gail Warrander and Venera Knaus:Kosovo.USA:Bradt Travel Guide, 2008 p.159</ref>

== Communist Structures in Peja ==
During the time when Kosovo was part of former Yugoslavia, Communist Architecture arised from the influence and was inspired by other communist countries (Russia). This style of architecture is also referred to as Stalinist Architecture, Stalinist Gothic, or Social Classicism.   
